uchard22歲。他與Katherine Smyth結婚。他們至少是1個兒子的父母。他去世於1073年在英國德比夏爾斯卡可利福享年24歲。"},"zh-hans":{"1049–1073":"1049年–1073年","1047–1074":"1047年–1074年","1073–1098":"1073年–1098年","1024–1090":"1024年–1090年","1027–1060":"1027年–1060年","1090":"1090年","1049":"1049年","1027":"1027年","1047":"1047年","1024":"1024年","1066":"1066年","1098":"1098年","LIV ABT 1070":"大约1070年","about 1048":"大约1048年","1074":"1074年","1073":"1073年","1060":"1060年","Avranches, Normandy, France":"法国諾門迪阿福朗徹斯","England":"英国英格兰","Stainesby, Derbyshire, England":"英国英格兰德比夏爾","Scarcliffe, Derby, Eng":"英国英格兰德比夏爾斯卡可利福","Scarcliffe, Derbyshire, England":"英国德比夏爾斯卡可利福","lifeSummary":"当Adam Le Savage于1049年出生在法国諾門迪阿福朗徹斯时，他的父亲John De Savage25岁，母亲Michel Bouchard22岁。他与Katherine Smyth结婚。他们至少是1个儿子的父母。他去世于1073年在英国德比夏爾斯卡可利福享年24岁。"},"hr":{"1049–1073":"1049.–1073.","1047–1074":"1047–1074","1073–1098":"1073.–1098","1024–1090":"1024–1090","1027–1060":"1027–1060.","1090":"1090","1049":"1049.","1027":"1027","1047":"1047","1024":"1024","1066":"1066","1098":"1098","LIV ABT 1070":"oko 1070.","about 1048":"oko 1048.","1074":"1074","1073":"1073.","1060":"1060.","Avranches, Normandy, France":"Avranches, Normandie, Francuska","England":"Engleska, United Kingdom","Stainesby, Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, Engleska, United Kingdom","Scarcliffe, Derby, Eng":"Scarcliffe, Derbyshire, Engleska, United Kingdom","Scarcliffe, Derbyshire, England":"Scarcliffe, Derbyshire, England"},"cs":{"1049–1073":"1049–1073","1047–1074":"1047–1074","1073–1098":"1073–1098","1024–1090":"1024–1090","1027–1060":"1027–1060","1090":"1090","1049":"1049","1027":"1027","1047":"1047","1024":"1024","1066":"1066","1098":"1098","LIV ABT 1070":"okolo 1070","about 1048":"okolo 1048","1074":"1074","1073":"1073","1060":"1060","Avranches, Normandy, France":"Avranches, Normandie, Francie","England":"Anglie, United Kingdom","Stainesby, Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, Anglie, United Kingdom","Scarcliffe, Derby, Eng":"Scarcliffe, Derbyshire, Anglie, United Kingdom","Scarcliffe, Derbyshire, England":"Scarcliffe, Derbyshire, Anglie"},"da":{"1049–1073":"1049–1073","1047–1074":"1047–1074","1073–1098":"1073–1098","1024–1090":"1024–1090","1027–1060":"1027–1060","1090":"1090","1049":"1049","1027":"1027","1047":"1047","1024":"1024","1066":"1066","1098":"1098","LIV ABT 1070":"omkring 1070","about 1048":"omkring 1048","1074":"1074","1073":"1073","1060":"1060","Avranches, Normandy, France":"Avranches, Normandie, Frankrig","England":"England, United Kingdom","Stainesby, Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom","Scarcliffe, Derby, Eng":"Scarcliffe, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom","Scarcliffe, Derbyshire, England":"Scarcliffe, Derbyshire, England"},"nl":{"1049–1073":"1049–1073","1047–1074":"1047–1074","1073–1098":"1073–1098","1024–1090":"1024–1090","1027–1060":"1027–1060","1090":"1090","1049":"1049","1027":"1027","1047":"1047","1024":"1024","1066":"1066","1098":"1098","LIV ABT 1070":"circa 1070","about 1048":"circa 1048","1074":"1074","1073":"1073","1060":"1060","Avranches, Normandy, France":"Avranches, Normandie, Frankrijk","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Stainesby, Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Scarcliffe, Derby, Eng":"Scarcliffe, Derbyshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Scarcliffe, Derbyshire, England":"Scarcliffe, Derbyshire, England"},"en":{"1049–1073":"1049–1073","1047–1074":"1047–1074","1073–1098":"1073–1098","1024–1090":"1024–1090","1027–1060":"1027–1060","1090":"1090","1049":"1049","1027":"1027","1047":"1047","1024":"1024","1066":"1066","1098":"1098","LIV ABT 1070":"about 1070","about 1048":"about 1048","1074":"1074","1073":"1073","1060":"1060","Avranches, Normandy, France":"Avranches, Normandy, France","England":"England, United Kingdom","Stainesby, Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom","Scarcliffe, Derby, Eng":"Scarcliffe, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom","Scarcliffe, Derbyshire, England":"Scarcliffe, Derbyshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Le","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Vietnamese Thanh, Hung, Minh, Dung, Tuan, Hai, Hoa, Thuy, Son, Anh, Long, Hoang.  Chinese Hong, Sang, Chi, Dong, Tong, Lai, Hang, Man, Han, Ho, Phoung, Chan.  Korean Tam, Phong, Nam, Thai, Tuong, Chung, Thach, Tinh, Manh, Tham, Uyen, Vang.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 樂, meaning ‘happiness’ in Chinese: from the first element of the personal name Le Fu (樂父), style name of Yan, son of the Duke Dai of Song (ruler of the state of Song, reigned 799–766  BC ). Yan's grandson Le Ju (樂莒) inherited Le (樂) as his surname.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 勒: (i) from the second element of the placename Shu-Le (疏勒), an ancient state (located in present-day Xinjiang Uyghur autonomous region) during the Western Han dynasty (206  BC –25  AD ). (ii) a surname near the Bohai Sea region during the Han dynasty (206  BC –220  AD ). (iii) a surname traced back to the Hun ethnic group in northern China during the Jin dynasty (265–420  AD )."],"variants":[{"name":"Yue","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese: Chi, Feng, Gang, Wei, Chun, Guo, Jin, Kin, Ping, Yan, Yun, Zhang, Chau, Du, Hau, Hung, My, Sau.","Chinese:","Mandarin form of the surname 岳 (or 嶽), meaning ‘high mountain’ in Chinese: traced back to Si Yue (四岳 or 四嶽), said to be the title of an official post in charge of sacrificial rituals on the site of famous mountains during the reign of the legendary Emperor Yao (<i>c.</i> 24th century  BC ) and Emperor Shun (<i>c.</i> 23rd century  BC )."]},{"name":"Lok","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Ping, Tat, Wing, Ying Lin, Chi Ming, Ching Wah, Chun, Chung Man, Han, Kam, Kam Tim, Kin.","Chinese: Cantonese form of the surname 樂, see   Le   1.","Chinese: Cantonese form of the surnames 陸, 鹿, 逯 and 禄, see   Lu   5 and (7-9)."]},{"name":"Li","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Wei, Ming, Li, Jian, Hong, Yan, Ping, Jing, Yong, Ying, Hui, Jin, Min, Chung.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 李, meaning ‘plum’: (i) said to have been adopted in place of the Chinese surname 理 (also pronounced Li; meaning ‘rules’ in Chinese) by Li Zhen (利貞), son of an official called Li Zheng (理徵) in the late Shang dynasty (1600–1046  BC ). It is said that Li Zhen's father incurred the displeasure of King Zhou of Shang (died 1046  BC ) and Li Zhen fled to a wasteland area, where he survived on wild plums. After his return to civilization, he changed his surname to Li (李 ‘plum’), a word with the same pronunciation. The original surname, 理, is said to be from Li Guan (理官), the name of a post of officials in charge of legislation in ancient China. Li Er (李耳), also known as Lao Tzu or Lao Zi, traditionally regarded as the founder of Taoism, is believed to have been a descendant of Li Zhen. (ii) adopted as a surname by the Chi Li (叱李) family from the Xianbei ethnic group during the Northern Wei dynasty (386–534  AD ). (iii) in the early years of the Tang dynasty (618–907  AD ), sixteen high officials with different surnames were granted the surname Li (李), the surname of the royal family of the Tang dynasty, by Emperor Taizong of Tang (died 649  BC ), because of their contributions to the establishment of the Tang regime. (iv) the surname can also be traced back to several minority ethnic groups in ancient China.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 黎, meaning ‘black’ or ‘multitude’ in ancient Chinese: (i) from Li (黎), the name of an ancient state (located in Changzhi in Shanxi province) during the Shang dynasty (1600–1046  BC ), which was annexed in the Western Zhou dynasty (1046–771  BC ) and later granted to Fengshu, also known as Li Hou (黎侯, 'Marquis Li'). (ii) adopted as a surname by the Su Li (素黎) family, members of the Xianbei ethnic group, during the Northern Wei dynasty (386–534  AD )."]}]},{"name":"Savage","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: of Norman origin, a nickname for a wild or uncouth person, from Middle English and Old French <i>salvage</i>, <i>sauvage</i> ‘wild, untamed’ (from Late Latin <i>salvaticus</i>, literally ‘man of the woods’, a derivative of Latin <i>silva</i> ‘wood’ influenced by Latin <i>salvus</i> ‘whole’, i.e. natural). Compare French   Sauvage  .","Irish (Down): generally of English origin (it was taken to County Down in the 12th century), this name has also sometimes been adopted as equivalent of Gaelic <b>Ó Sabháin</b>, the name of a small south Munster sept, which was earlier Anglicized as <b>O'Savin</b> (see   Savin  ).","Americanized form of Jewish (Ashkenazic)   Savich   and of Serbian <b>Savić</b> (see   Savic  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Savitt","meanings":["Possibly English or Irish: variant of   Savage  . This surname is very rare in Britain.","Alternatively, perhaps an Americanized form of Jewish   Savich   or an American shortened and altered form of Jewish   Savitski  ."]},{"name":"Sauvage","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Michel, Armand, Jean-Jacques.","French and Channel Islands: nickname for a wild or uncouth person, from Old French <i>salvage</i>, <i>sauvage</i> ‘untamed’ (from Late Latin <i>salvaticus</i>, a derivative of Latin <i>silva</i> ‘wood’, influenced by Latin <i>salvus</i> ‘whole’, i.e. natural). This surname is also found in England.","History: Jean Sauvage from Plouëc-du-Trieux in Côtes-d'Armor, Brittany (France), married Marguerite Martin in Les Cèdres, QC, in 1782."]},{"name":"Salvage","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Monique.","English (Sussex): variant of   Savage  .","Americanized form of some similar (like-sounding) Jewish surname."]},{"name":"Ramage","meanings":["Scottish and English (of Norman origin); French: nickname for a savage or unpredictable individual, from Old French <i>ramage</i> ‘wild, untamed’. The word is recorded once in Middle English with the sense ‘courageous’ and in Scots (spelled <i>rammage</i>) as ‘rash, furious’. Compare   Savage  ."]},{"name":"Sabin","meanings":["English (Warwickshire and Northamptonshire): from the Middle English personal name <i>Sabin</i> (from Latin <i>Sabinus</i>; see 2 below) or its female equivalent <i>Sabine</i> (from Latin <i>Sabina</i>). In medieval England the feminine form was always more popular as a personal name.","French: from the Old French personal name <i>Sabin</i>, from Latin <i>Sabinus</i>. The name was originally referred to the Sabines, an ancient Italic people of central Italy whose name is of uncertain origin. In the 8th century  BC  the Romans slaughtered the Sabine menfolk and carried off the women. More influential as far as name-giving is concerned was the existence of several early Christian saints named <i>Sabinus</i>.","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Sabháin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Sabhán</i>’, a personal name based on <i>sabh</i> ‘cub’. As an Irish surname, this has mostly been absorbed into   Savage  ."]},{"name":"Selvidge","meanings":["English (Leicestershire):","from Middle English <i>selvage</i>, <i>silvadge</i> ‘edge of a cloth, bandage, ornamental edging (to a cloth or garment)’, hence a nickname for someone who made or sold such items.","variant of   Savage  ."]},{"name":"Savidge","meanings":["English: variant of   Savage  ."]}]},{"name":"Adam","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical.  See  <b>Adam</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705182,"age":17,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Adam Le Savage was born in 1049, in Avranches, Normandy, France, his father, John De Savage, was 25 and his mother, Michel Bouchard, was 22. He married Katherine Smyth. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1073, in Scarcliffe, Derbyshire, England, at the age of 24."},"et":{"1049–1073":"1049–1073","1047–1074":"1047–1074","1073–1098":"1073–1098","1024–1090":"1024–1090","1027–1060":"1027–1060","1090":"1090","1049":"1049","1027":"1027","1047":"1047","1024":"1024","1066":"1066","1098":"1098","LIV ABT 1070":"umbes 1070","about 1048":"umbes 1048","1074":"1074","1073":"1073","1060":"1060","Avranches, Normandy, France":"Avranches, Normandie, Prantsusmaa","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Stainesby, Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Scarcliffe, Derby, Eng":"Scarcliffe, Derbyshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Scarcliffe, Derbyshire, England":"Scarcliffe, Derbyshire, England"},"fi":{"1049–1073":"1049–1073","1047–1074":"1047–1074","1073–1098":"1073–1098","1024–1090":"1024–1090","1027–1060":"1027–1060","1090":"1090","1049":"1049","1027":"1027","1047":"1047","1024":"1024","1066":"1066","1098":"1098","LIV ABT 1070":"noin 1070","about 1048":"noin 1048","1074":"1074","1073":"1073","1060":"1060","Avranches, Normandy, France":"Avranches, Normandie, Ranska","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Stainesby, Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Scarcliffe, Derby, Eng":"Scarcliffe, Derbyshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Scarcliffe, Derbyshire, England":"Scarcliffe, Derbyshire, England"},"fr":{"1049–1073":"1049–1073","1047–1074":"1047–1074","1073–1098":"1073–1098","1024–1090":"1024–1090","1027–1060":"1027–1060","1090":"1090","1049":"1049","1027":"1027","1047":"1047","1